        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">CDLR Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">CDLR Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        CDLR: Chain Driven Live Roller Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A CDLR (Chain Driven Live Roller) conveyor uses roller chains and sprockets to positively drive conveyor rollers, providing zero-slip heavy-duty transport for pallets, drums, heavy cases, and other loads from 500 to over 10,000 lbs. CDLR conveyors serve as the standard powered conveyor technology for <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pallet handling systems</a>, end-of-line packaging, and any application where product weight exceeds the capacity of belt-driven or <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR roller conveyors</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How CDLR Works -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Technical Deep-Dive</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How CDLR Conveyors <span class="text-accent">Work</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Each roller in a CDLR conveyor has a sprocket welded or keyed to one end. A continuous roller chain loop wraps around adjacent roller sprockets, connecting them in pairs or in a single continuous strand. A gearmotor at one end drives the chain, which positively rotates every roller in the section. The chain provides mechanical positive engagement , rollers turn regardless of product weight, surface friction, or load distribution.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Chain Drive Configurations</h3>
        <p>CDLR conveyors use two primary chain drive configurations. In the <strong class="text-ink">continuous chain strand</strong> configuration, a single chain loops around all roller sprockets in the section, driven by the gearmotor sprocket. This provides uniform speed across all rollers. In the <strong class="text-ink">paired chain</strong> configuration, short chain loops connect adjacent roller pairs. The drive roller transfers motion to the first pair, which transfers to the next pair via the chain loop. Paired chains are easier to maintain because replacing one chain segment does not require dismantling the entire drive.</p>

        <p>Standard CDLR chains use ANSI #40 (1/2" pitch) for light-medium duty and ANSI #50 (5/8" pitch) or #60 (3/4" pitch) for heavy-duty pallet applications. Chain guards protect operators and prevent debris from entering the chain path. Hytrol, Dematic, and Intelligrated offer CDLR systems with both continuous and paired chain configurations.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Common ANSI chain sizes for Hytrol CDLR models -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Roller Construction</h3>
        <p>CDLR rollers are heavier-duty than standard powered roller or <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/gravity/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">gravity roller</a> designs. Typical CDLR roller diameters range from 2.5" to 3.5". Wall thickness ranges from 11-gauge (0.120") for medium cases to 7-gauge (0.180") for heavy pallets. Axle diameters range from 11/16" to 1-3/16" hex or round. Heavy-duty sealed bearings (ABEC-1 or higher) support the roller loads. Roller pitch (spacing) is typically 3", 4", 6", or wider depending on product size.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Frame Construction</h3>
        <p>CDLR frames use heavier steel than standard roller conveyor frames. Medium-duty frames use 10-gauge formed channel. Heavy-duty pallet CDLR uses 7-gauge structural channel or structural tube frames. Frame widths range from 24" to 60" between rails for pallet applications. Hytrol's heavy-duty CDLR line and Dematic's pallet conveyor platform use structural steel frames with bolt-together construction for field assembly.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Speed and Control</h3>
        <p>CDLR conveyors operate at 20-120 FPM. Most pallet CDLR applications run at 20-60 FPM. <a href="/resources/conveyor-motors-drives/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Variable frequency drives</a> (VFDs) provide adjustable speed control. CDLR sections integrate with PLC controls for start/stop sequencing, photo-eye product detection, and coordination with upstream and downstream equipment. Multiple CDLR sections can operate at different speeds to create accumulation zones, though CDLR does not typically provide zero-pressure accumulation , products accumulate with full backpressure unless mechanical stops or pneumatic pop-ups are added.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- When to Use CDLR -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="when-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
      <h2 id="when-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        When to Use CDLR vs <span class="text-accent">Other Roller Types</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>CDLR occupies the heavy-duty end of the <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyor</a> spectrum. Choose CDLR over other roller conveyor types in these scenarios:</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Product weight exceeds 500 lbs.</strong> <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a> top out at approximately 250 lbs per zone. <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/powered/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Belt-driven live roller</a> handles up to 500 lbs. CDLR handles 500-10,000+ lbs with positive chain drive. Any loaded pallet application typically requires CDLR.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Zero slip is required.</strong> Belt-driven and O-ring-driven roller conveyors rely on friction to transfer drive force. Heavy loads, wet surfaces, or dusty environments can cause belt or O-ring slip. CDLR's chain-and-sprocket engagement provides positive drive with zero slip regardless of surface conditions.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Poor product bottom surface.</strong> Products with uneven, wet, or low-friction bottoms may not grip belt-driven rollers. CDLR rollers rotate regardless of the product's bottom surface condition , the chain drives the rollers whether or not the product slips on them.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Choose MDR or BDLR instead when:</strong> products weigh under 250-500 lbs, you need zone-controlled <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation</a>, noise is a concern (CDLR runs at 75-85 dB vs MDR at 55-65 dB), or energy efficiency is a priority. MDR provides superior zone control and energy savings for lighter loads. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/live-roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">live roller conveyor comparison</a> for a detailed head-to-head analysis.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

