            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Relative Cost</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$-$$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">$$$-$$$$</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">Specifications represent typical ranges from Hytrol, Dematic, and Intelligrated CDLR product lines. See <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cost guide</a> for pricing factors.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        CDLR Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Pallet conveyor systems:</strong> CDLR is the default drive technology for <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pallet conveyor systems</a>. Loaded pallets (typically 1,500-3,500 lbs) transport between palletizers, stretch wrappers, labelers, and shipping docks on CDLR conveyors. Right-angle chain <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfers</a> route pallets to multiple shipping lanes.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Drum and barrel handling:</strong> Steel drums and barrels (500-2,000 lbs) ride on CDLR rollers. The positive chain drive prevents the slip issues that belt-driven systems experience with round, smooth drum surfaces. Chemical, petroleum, and <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food processing</a> facilities use CDLR for drum transport.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Heavy case transport:</strong> Cases and totes exceeding 200 lbs , such as automotive parts, appliance components, and heavy industrial goods , use CDLR conveyors. The positive chain drive handles variable loads without the speed variation that belt-driven systems exhibit under changing load conditions.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Between palletizer and stretch wrapper:</strong> The section between the palletizer discharge and the stretch wrapper infeed is one of the most critical CDLR applications in <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging lines</a>. Full pallets (often 2,000-3,500 lbs) must transfer reliably at 20-40 FPM with precise positioning for the stretch wrapper's turntable or ring wrapper. CDLR provides the torque and positive drive this application demands.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">With <a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">vertical reciprocating conveyors</a>:</strong> CDLR sections feed loaded pallets onto VRC platforms for multi-level transport. The positive chain drive ensures reliable loading/unloading of the VRC even with heavy, off-center pallet loads.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Maintenance -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="maintenance-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Maintenance</div>
      <h2 id="maintenance-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        CDLR <span class="text-accent">Maintenance</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>CDLR conveyors require more maintenance than <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a> but handle loads that MDR cannot. Key maintenance items include:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Chain lubrication:</strong> Apply chain lubricant monthly for standard-duty applications, weekly for heavy continuous duty. Use food-grade lubricant (H1) in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food and beverage</a> environments. Under-lubricated chains wear 3-5x faster.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Chain tension:</strong> Check chain tension quarterly. Loose chains skip sprocket teeth and cause roller speed variation. Over-tight chains accelerate bearing and sprocket wear.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Sprocket inspection:</strong> Inspect sprocket teeth for hooked, worn, or broken profiles annually. Replace sprockets when tooth wear reaches 50% of original tooth thickness.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Chain replacement:</strong> Replace chains when stretch exceeds 3% of original length. Properly lubricated ANSI roller chains last 3-5 years in standard pallet handling. Replace all chains in a section simultaneously to maintain uniform speed.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Bearing and roller inspection:</strong> Check for rough-running, seized, or noisy bearings semi-annually. Replace failed rollers individually without dismantling the chain drive.</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- VERIFY: Chain replacement interval and stretch percentage threshold from ANSI/ASME standards -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What does CDLR stand for?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>CDLR stands for Chain Driven Live Roller. Roller chains and sprockets positively drive all rollers with zero slip. CDLR is the standard for heavy-duty <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pallet conveying</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is the weight capacity of a CDLR conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Standard: 500-4,000 lbs. Heavy-duty structural: up to 10,000+ lbs. Capacity depends on roller diameter, wall thickness, bearing type, frame gauge, and chain size.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            When should I use CDLR instead of MDR?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Use CDLR when product weight exceeds 250-500 lbs, you need zero-slip positive drive, or product bottoms have poor friction. Use <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR</a> for lighter loads needing zone control and <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What maintenance does CDLR require?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Monthly chain lubrication, quarterly chain tension checks, annual sprocket inspection, and chain replacement every 3-5 years (when stretch exceeds 3%). Motor/gearbox lubrication per manufacturer schedule.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ink-light" aria-labelledby="related-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
